description.narrative: By end 2021, government actors, communities and NGOs in targeted zones have the capacity to prepare for and mount a coordinated response to the need for inclusive education in emergencies, in line with INEE standards, which contributes to Education In Emergencies, Equitable Access To Quality Education, Equitable Access To Quality Education (Covid), Learning And Child-Friendly Schools, Learning Outcomes, Skills Development. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 5: By the end of 2021, the most vulnerable preschool and school-age children, adolescents and young people, of both sexes, in the 10 targeted provinces make greater use of inclusive, quality educational services, for improved learning outcomes and receive certification for this.

description.narrative: Despite the low level of funding for education in emergencies (only 52 per cent funded), the Government of Chad, with the support of its partners, including UNICEF, has been able to provide education for children in humanitarian situations. Chad has a National Contingency Plan for Education (PNCET) covering the period 2020-2024. It should be noted that whilst the populations in the Lake Chad area are still forced to move, the refugee and displaced populations in the south, and especially in the east, have somewhat settled and the humanitarian-development continuum has therefore become a reality in Chad. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:08/02/2020
